{
  "id": "c-moa42rxh-d965072428ba",
  "goal": "Design the vision-keeper role — the agent/apparatus that holds a forward-looking product vision and decomposes it into commissionable work",
  "status": "live",
  "createdAt": "2026-04-22T13:51:35.909Z",
  "parentId": "c-mod99ris-572b67f97ce0",
  "links": {
    "outbound": [],
    "inbound": [
      {
        "id": "c-mob1w13b-91635892d2fe:c-moa42rxh-d965072428ba:related",
        "sourceId": "c-mob1w13b-91635892d2fe",
        "targetId": "c-moa42rxh-d965072428ba",
        "linkType": "related",
        "createdAt": "2026-04-23T18:20:09.295Z"
      }
    ]
  },
  "parent": {
    "id": "c-mod99ris-572b67f97ce0",
    "goal": "Design the Reckoner — petition scheduler that accepts petitions from registered petitioners (vision-keepers, tech-debt watchers, laboratory/introspection, etc.), weighs them against guild priorities and resource constraints (concurrency, token budget), and determines which petitions get dispatched as writs",
    "status": "live"
  },
  "children": {
    "summary": {
      "concluded": 18,
      "parked": 5,
      "live": 5
    },
    "items": [
      {
        "id": "c-moivkfgb-c572ddcebd48",
        "goal": "Priority dimension cascade — when a review rig posts child review mandates for the next layer down, do those children inherit / get bounded by the parent petition's priority dimensions, or are they fresh claims per child? Lean: parent priority should function as an UPPER BOUND on child priorities (a vision-neutral vision shouldn't spawn vision-blocker charges). For v0: skip the bounding mechanism — let rigs claim whatever priorities they choose for children. Revisit if observed mis-claims or runaway escalation surface in the Reckonings log.",
        "status": "live"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-moivkc4y-f8def200d3e2",
        "goal": "Output contract for review rigs — what does a review-vision/review-charge/review-piece rig produce as its own resolution? Side effects (child cartograph nodes, child review mandates) are clear, but does the rig's writ completion carry a summary, a list of created child writ ids, an analysis report, or simply a bare 'completed' phase with no resolution payload? Affects observability, replay, and any downstream apparatus that wants to know what a review round produced without scanning the writ tree.",
        "status": "live"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-moivk9qw-ce632baebd3d",
        "goal": "Number of rigs in v0 vision-keeper — single recursive review rig that handles all layers, or three layer-specific rigs (review-vision, review-charge, review-piece)?",
        "status": "concluded"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-moivk8yc-b26d733e6745",
        "goal": "Withdrawal cascade direction — when a cartograph node is cancelled or dropped mid-flight, does that cascade to in-flight petitions/mandates under it?",
        "status": "concluded"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-moivk7pd-7bedba64b71a",
        "goal": "Lifecycle interactions between Reckoner gating, arbitrary writ types' custom lifecycles, and inter-writ relationships. Reckoner uses new→open as the accept transition — this works cleanly for mandates but assumes the writ type's active phase is named 'open'. How does this generalize to writ types with custom lifecycles (e.g. cartograph charges/pieces have draft|active|... stages and may have non-'open' first active phases)? Second concern: there is currently no way to DRAFT a writ before sending it to the petitioner other than omitting ext.reckoner — once ext is set, the writ is live for Reckoner consideration. This means parent/child or 'follows' dependency relationships cannot be set up before dispatch without risking the target writ being accepted and dispatched before its dependents are wired. Third concern: deadlock potential — if the Reckoner has a WIP limit and accepts a batch of writs that all 'follows'-depend on unaccepted petitions still queued, the accepted writs sit blocked waiting on petitions that may never get capacity to be considered. Need to think through whether a draft-state-before-petition mechanism is needed, whether dependencies should be Reckoner-aware (defer accept until dependencies are clear), and how active-phase naming generalizes per writ-type.",
        "status": "concluded"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-moiu8tm4-52624db7f9cd",
        "goal": "Periodic re-evaluation of long-lived cartograph nodes — visions especially are durable and the world drifts around them; the canonical Reckoner-contract example (vision-keeper.snapshot) was literally drift detection. v0 lean from this conversation: a manual command (nsg vision review <id> or similar) that posts a review-vision mandate against an existing vision. Future shape (post-v0): scheduled re-review via Clockworks tick or Reckoner deferUntil; or a separate drift-sentinel apparatus that observes the world and emits its own snapshot petitions. Open: does the manual command live in cartograph CLI, vision-keeper CLI, or as a generic 'request review of writ X' surface? Does the same surface work for charges/pieces, or are visions special?",
        "status": "live"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-moiu8pm9-60d67f5af591",
        "goal": "Initial petition timing — when does the first review-vision mandate land for a newly-created vision? Three candidates: (a) patron posts it manually after createVision (extra step, but explicit and gives patron a chance to seed priority dimensions per vision), (b) cartograph emits it as part of createVision (couples data layer to vision-keeper logic — bad layering), (c) vision-keeper apparatus subscribes to CDC on book.cartograph.visions.created and emits the initial review-vision mandate (clean layering, autonomous, vision-keeper owns its observation surface). Same question recurs for charges and pieces if upstream rigs create them — does the rig that creates a charge also post the review-charge mandate in the same transaction, or is there a CDC observer that fires on any cartograph-node-created event?",
        "status": "live"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-moiu7yc1-b4aa16803c7d",
        "goal": "Petitioner runtime overall shape — does decomposition happen via a watching loop that reacts to ladder state, or via a recursive cascade where each layer's elaboration is itself a Reckoner-gated petition that competes for guild resources alongside implementation work?",
        "status": "concluded"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-mod53rpa-34d17875d4e5",
        "goal": "Plan for cross-product dependency edges in the writ data model (deferred, but model must leave room)",
        "status": "parked"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-mod53rbz-c46fc868493d",
        "goal": "How is Nexus's first product-vision captured — one-shot patron-authored document or iterative elicitation ceremony?",
        "status": "parked"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-mod53q2r-e7d500fa4d4a",
        "goal": "Should decomposition-ladder authoring be patron-only for v0, or Reckoner-proposes-patron-ratifies from day one?",
        "status": "concluded"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-mod53p9w-4cfd83384603",
        "goal": "Dogfood Nexus as the first product: author vision and initial capabilities through the new machinery",
        "status": "parked"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-mod53ood-521f606db4b9",
        "goal": "Design the ladder shape — product is the fixed top; one named first-decomposition type (feature/capability) under product; recursive decomposition node type below that can self-nest to arbitrary depth; mandate attaches at any depth under feature ('no shortcuts from product to mandate'). How many fixed levels, what node types exist at each, and where mandates are allowed to attach.",
        "status": "concluded"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-mod53o6h-5605d3c29086",
        "goal": "Introduce product as a first-class writ type; patron owns all visions (client proxy stays private). Portfolio is implicit (1:1 with guild/patron/all-products) for v0 — revisit if any of those become 1:N.",
        "status": "concluded"
      }
    ]
  }
}

